On Sat, Mar 10, 2012 at 1:24 PM, Jan Algermissen &lt;jan.algermissen@...
&gt; wrote:

&gt;
&gt; On Mar 10, 2012, at 10:18 PM, Jan Algermissen wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; On Mar 10, 2012, at 10:06 PM, Glenn Block wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; Thanks Jan
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; If am reading the deck properly you are saying the application includes
&gt; the client / server components, the client is not separate. Is that correct?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Yes, the *user agent* (&#39;client&#39; is the term for the connector, not the
&gt; component) is just another component of the application that realizes some
&gt; use case.
&gt;
&gt; And also note, that the user agent component &#39;extends&#39; all the way to the
&gt; user. It is the component, the user interacts[1] with, not just the HTTP
&gt; lib with caching and such magic.
&gt;
&gt; [1] Even if that interaction only takes place at use case execution start
&gt; time and use case result review time. Some use cases involve lots of user
&gt; action steps (e.g. purchasing a book at Amazon), some don&#39;t (e.g.
&gt; automatically crawling 10 shops and placing an automatic order at lowest
&gt; price found).
&gt;
&gt; GB: Yes that makes sense. Client is an overloaded term as often when
general developers speak about client they mean the user agent i.e.
Silverlight client, Flash client, web client etc. I was using it in that
sens.


&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; There is conceptually no difference between a monolithic application and
&gt; a networked application. It is just that in the latter the components
&gt; reside on different hosts (e.g. your PC and Amazon&#39;s server host).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Note how the configuration of the app is different! A monolithic
&gt; application is configured (assembled) at compile time, a unix commandline
&gt; is configured when you type it (search for &#39;invisible hand&#39; in the
&gt; dissertation) and an HTTP (browser based) application is configured when
&gt; you type the URI(s) in your browser window(s).
&gt;

GB: Sure, but from an HTTP perspective all I care about is what is going
across the wire / or passing through intermediaries.

&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Not browser-based HTTP applications are configured when the user agent
&gt; component (e.g. the crawler that checks some online shops) is configured
&gt; with its start URIs.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Jan
